                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d679">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">861.00/8692: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Bell</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1921-06-07T18:00:00+09:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">June 7, 1921—6 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received 7:40 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>197. Last paragraph my no. 192 of June 2. The military attaché has been informed
                    by the War Office that the Japanese military attaché in Washington was called in
                    by you and that you spoke to him on this subject very strongly. The War Office
                    was greatly disturbed to have the American Government think that the Japanese
                    acted in an unneutral way. They state that according to more recent information
                    it is indicated that Semenov took supplies but did not take arms and ammunition,
                    and that only about sixty officers accompanied him. Japanese authorities for the
                    last few days have insisted that they are keeping strictly neutral in
                    Vladivostok, that they sought to persuade Semenov not to leave Port Arthur, and
                    that they are putting difficulties in the way of his landing. Nevertheless it is
                    true that Semenov did leave Port Arthur, sailing on a Japanese ship which he
                    chartered.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Bell</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
